<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 93 / International Company News: US airline broadens European
talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Bob Crandall, chairman of American Airlines, said yesterday the US
carrier had held talks over possible partnerships with a number of European
carriers, including Lufthansa, British Midland, Air France, SAS, and KLM
Royal Dutch Airlines.
Speaking after his company's annual meeting in Texas, Mr Crandall said: 'We
haven't been able to structure a deal that makes sense for us and a European
partner.' However, talks were continuing.
Although talks in the past had covered equity investments, discussions under
way now were more about marketing relationships, he said.
Mr Crandall's comments come in the wake of a number of tie-ups between US
and European carriers - including British Airways' purchase of a minority
interest in USAir, KLM's integration with Northwest Airlines, and the
partnership between Air Canada and Continental.
</TEXT>
